@node Intro
@{b}@{u}INTRODUCTION: @{ub}@{uu}

This disk contains two programs that can be used to transfer data between C64 and Amiga computers. 
When I first used these programs I found a lack of information in the documentation. Therefore I started to write some additional texts/scripts to ease the use of the two programs. 
Also you will find a lot of music-files which are some I have ripped a long time ago... To play these files a SID-emulater have been included.

The two programs I mentioned before are JNet and PData, which are using the same nullmodem-cable. In order to use them you will need to construct this cable(!). This is quite easy - The only problem is from which view you see the @{"pins" link "Amiga2c64:S/User-Interface.IFF/MAIN"}.

Before you try to start any script or program on this disk you should click on the icon called 'Temporary Setup'. This will add a few assigns to your system - But don't worry nothing will be changed on your HD...
@endnode

@node JNet
@{b}@{u}JNET: @{ub}@{uu}

Start up SHELL and go to the Jnet-Drawer where you will find a small ASCII file called @{"LOADSAVE.ASC" link "Amiga2c64:JNet/LOADSAVE.ASC/MAIN"}. This is a small basic program, which you have to type on your C64.
When this is done you simply execute the 'jnet.startup' program, also located in the JNet-Drawer. Now follow the instructions...

Hopefully you have now started the JNet-transfer program, which means that you have an extra I/O-device on your C64. This device is used exactly like any other device on the C64 - The only difference is that the data is stored on the Amiga Ram-Disk!
For example if you want to transfer a program to the Amiga, you could do like this:

		SAVE "COBRA",7

This is very easy and works out great, but unfortunally it is not able to transfer files that is located in $CE2C-$C???, because the transfer code is located in this area.
Also when you load a program from the C64-floppydisk, and it is located between $B000-$C000, you will get an error-message when you try to save it
again. This is a normal procedure for the C64 and in order to stop these error-messages you can press RUNSTOP/RESTORE. 
When this is done, you still can't save your program because the program-settings have just been erased by the RUNSTOP/RESTORE combination... You can get around this by a POKE-command, but I can't remember it:(

Use JNet with programs located between @{u}$0801 - $AFFF@{uu}

@endnode

@node PData
@{b}@{u}PDATA: @{ub}@{uu}

If you want to use PData, you will have to transfer the C64-part of the program to the C64.
To do this, you can either contact the author of PData, or you can use 'JNet'. The last option is probably the easiest way to handle the situation, so now you start JNet as descriped under @{"JNet" link JNet}.

Now copy the file 'PData.C64' to the Ram-disk and rename it to 'PData'. Then type the following on the C64:

		LOAD "PDATA 3.3-SHARKS",7

And in a few seconds, you will have the PData.C64 loaded to the C64! The only thing to do now is to run it...
In the PData main-menu, you can chose to save the PData program to your floppy disk so that you don't have to see the introes everytime you start up PData.

With PData you can transfer ANY file you want.

@endnode

@node MusicRips
@{b}@{u}Music Rips: @{ub}@{uu}

The main reason why I started this project was that I wanted to use all of my old music-rips from the C64 with the SID-Player by Per Hňkon Sundell & Ron Birk.
And here they are ... The transfer was quite painless but when it came to the actual playing with SID-Player the trouble began. 
When the music is initialized it could go like this:

		LDA #$00
		JSR $0900

This is no problem for the SID-Player but a lot of music uses LDX instead of LDA and then SID-Player can't initialize.
In order to avoid this problem I had to make additional code to the music-files. So I started up the A64-emulator which have a nice debugger - Perfect for C64 machine-language!

Besides of all the music-files you will find two archives which contains some C64-demoes from Unit 2 (our group!) and some very old C64 games...

@endnode
